omponents; but rather exploits the synergy that can be obtained by combining the strengths of different types of sensor, in a holistic approach to intrusion management design.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-07-27</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/798CB33D-C79E-4578-83F2-72606407192C"><gtr:id>798CB33D-C79E-4578-83F2-72606407192C</gtr:id><gtr:name>EPSRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-09-28</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>228258</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>We have demonstrated out work to CESG. We are also beginning to use the background expertise to apply for further funding to the EU, envisaged in 2015.</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2014</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>0B3ED388-2EEB-4C1C-AB14-4C5FE001D531</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes/><gtr:sector>Digital/Communication/Information Technologies (including Software),Security and Diplomacy</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>The project was highly collaborative (with Cranfield, our academic partner). The primary outcomes of the work are: 

a) The production of a system deployment model (winner of a best paper prize) that allows various deployments to be compared and optimised.

b) The development of a multi-criteria optimisation framework allowing various deployment evaluation criteria to be traded of against each other. The deployments are evaluated via off-line simulation using randomly generated loads and attacks. The approach uses evolutionary computation and simulated annealing.

c) The production of a Bayesian model for identifying insider agents in network as new information is received.

d) The production of papers regarding sensors and their characterisation and also difficult areas for intrusion detection</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>Our best paper prize initiates a discussion about the value of deployments. We think much more work can and should be done on this angle to place intrusion detection on a principled basis. 

Furthermore the work on probe placement (essentially optimal use of resources) could be extended to deal with finer matters of configuration over and above location. Thus, the general optimisation approach can be applied to dynamic configuration of audit logging. 

We believe also that our Bayesian insider agent model can find application in real networks.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>AA23206F-898F-4BFE-933B-A0349E02245F</gtr:id><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Digital/Communication/Information Technologies (including Software),Security and Diplomacy</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors><gtr:url>http://www.cs.york.ac.uk/security/projSSID.html</gtr:url></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/BCF88459-B492-4335-BD3C-AEE3AC0CA7D9"><gtr:id>BCF88459-B492-4335-BD3C-AEE3AC0CA7D9</gtr:id><gtr:title>Knowing Who to Watch: Efficiently Identifying Subtle Attackers</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Information Systems Frontiers: Special Edition on Insider Attacks</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/4363f19faaccb3f58a089c5a8764008f"><gtr:id>4363f19faaccb3f58a089c5a8764008f</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>n/a Chivers</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2010-01-01</gtr:date></gtr:publication><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/333E4886-F812-4E84-8E2B-4B4960E6ED85"><gtr:id>333E4886-F812-4E84-8E2B-4B4960E6ED85</gtr:id><gtr:title>Optimising IDS Sensor Placement</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/36e6bd83dfd373c441dfe6211f736a6c"><gtr:id>36e6bd83dfd373c441dfe6211f736a6c</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Chen H</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2010-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:isbn>978-1-4244-5879-0</gtr:isbn></gtr:publication><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/BBFEE2FA-D9CF-4DD4-8AE3-90B717829612"><gtr:id>BBFEE2FA-D9CF-4DD4-8AE3-90B717829612</gtr:id><gtr:title>Accumulating Evidence of Insider Attacks</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:aut